Researchers in Denmark recently discovered that diabetes is linked to an
Type 1 diabetes is linked to a 33% increase in the risk of falls, while type 2
diabetes is linked to a 19% increased risk of falls.
The fall risk for people with diabetes is higher because their blood glucose
fluctuates, they can have health complications, and often use more medication
The study was presented at the annual meeting of the European Association for
The study aimed to estimate the risk of falls and the risk factors linked to
increased falls in people with diabetes compared with the general population.
The second aim was to estimate fall-related injuries including fractures and
The data was taken from the Nationwide Danish National Patient Register.
The team identified 12,975 people with type 1 diabetes and 407,099 people with
type 2 diabetes and matched a control group from the general population.
They found type 1 diabetes was linked to a 33% increased risk of a first fall,
and type 2 diabetes a 19% increased risk.
Other risk factors for those with type 1 and type 2 diabetes included:
* use of selective serotonin receptor inhibitors (SSRIs) generally used to treat depression
* a history of alcohol abuse. This near doubling of risk).
People with type 2 diabetes also suffered an increased incidence of fractures
There was an increased risk of fractures of the hip and femur, bones in the
People with type 1 diabetes also had an increased risk of fractures, but only
The team says older people with diabetes need to pay more attention to the
risk factors for falls. Improving strength and balance can help manage these
If you're interested in improving your strength and balance check out these
